[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] In the most basic formulation of arc length for a parametric curve (thought of as the trajectory of a particle, moving in the plane with position $(x(t),y(t))$ at time t ) the arc length is obtained by integrating speed (the magnitude of the velocity vector) over the curve with respect to time.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] Thus the length of a continuously differentiable curve in the Euclidean plane, parameterized as $(x(t),y(t))$ , for $a\leq t\leq b$ , is given as the integral $L=\int _{a}^{b}{\sqrt {x'(t)^{2}+y'(t)^{2}}}\,dt.$ Here the integrand (the square root inside the integral) is the particle's speed.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] This defining integral of arc length does not always have a closed-form expression, and numerical integration may be used instead to obtain numerical values of arc length.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] More generally, for curves that are not necessarily in the plane, let $f\colon [a,b]\to \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ be continuously differentiable (i.e., the derivative is a continuous function) function.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] The length of the curve is given by the formula $L(f)=\int _{a}^{b}|f'(t)|\,dt$ where $|f'(t)|$ is the Euclidean norm of the tangent vector $f'(t)$ to the curve.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] A curve can be parameterized in infinitely many ways.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] The arc length of the curve is the same regardless of the parameterization used to define the curve.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] A curve in the plane can be approximated by connecting a finite number of points on the curve, in consecutive order, using (straight) line segments to create a polygonal chain.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] One may calculate the length of each linear segment using the Pythagorean theorem, and sum these lengths to obtain the total length of the chain; that approximation is known as the *(cumulative) chordal distance*.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] If additional points are placed along the curve, the chordal distance will not decrease.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] It can increase to a finite bound, in the limit, as the length of the longest segment in the chain decreases to zero, or it can increase without bound.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] In the case where the length of the refined polygonal chain increases to a finite bound, this bound is the length of the curve.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] For a smooth curve of finite length, this limiting length always equals the length obtained from integration, but this limit-based definition of length also applies to certain non-smooth curves.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] A curve with the property that every arc between two points of the curve has finite length, when measured in this way, is called a rectifiable curve, even if the whole curve has infinite length.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] A **signed arc length** can be defined to convey a sense of orientation or "direction" with respect to a reference point taken as origin in the curve (see also: curve orientation and signed distance).
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] Curves with closed-form solutions for arc length include the catenary, circle, cycloid, logarithmic spiral, parabola, semicubical parabola and straight line.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] The lack of a closed form solution for the arc length of an elliptic and hyperbolic arc led to the development of the elliptic integrals.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] In most cases, including even simple curves, there are no closed-form solutions for arc length and numerical integration is necessary.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] Because of the differentiation in the arc-length formula, the integrand's Taylor series loses one order of precision, relative to the arc itself, with a corresponding loss of precision.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] But for infinitely smooth functions, numerical integration of the arc length integral is usually very efficient.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] For example, consider the problem of finding the length of a quarter of the unit circle by numerically integrating the arc length integral.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] The upper half of the unit circle can be parameterized as $y={\sqrt {1-x^{2}}}.$ The interval $x\in \left[-{\tfrac {\sqrt {2}}{2}},{\tfrac {\sqrt {2}}{2}}\right]$ corresponds to a quarter of the circle.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] This means it is possible to evaluate this integral to almost machine precision with only 16 integrand evaluations.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] Let $\mathbf {x} (u,v)$ be a surface mapping and let $\mathbf {C} (t)=(u(t),v(t))$ be a curve on this surface.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] (where $g_{ij}$ is the first fundamental form coefficient), so the integrand of the arc length integral can be written as ${\sqrt {g_{ab}\left(u^{a}\right)'\left(u^{b}\right)'\,}}$ (where $u^{1}=u$ and $u^{2}=v$ ).
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] Let $\mathbf {C} (t)=(r(t),\theta (t))$ be a curve expressed in polar coordinates.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] The second expression is for a polar graph $r=r(\theta )$ parameterized by $t=\theta$ .
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] Now let $\mathbf {C} (t)=(r(t),\theta (t),\phi (t))$ be a curve expressed in spherical coordinates where $\theta$ is the polar angle measured from the positive x -axis and $\phi$ is the azimuthal angle.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] Arc lengths are denoted by *s*, since the Latin word for length (or size) is *spatium*.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] In the following lines, r represents the radius of a circle, d is its diameter, C is its circumference, s is the length of an arc of the circle, and $\theta$ is the angle which the arc subtends at the centre of the circle.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] The distances $r,d,C,$ and s are expressed in the same units.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] Two units of length, the nautical mile and the metre (or kilometre), were originally defined so the lengths of arcs of great circles on the Earth's surface would be simply numerically related to the angles they subtend at its centre.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] The lengths of the distance units were chosen to make the circumference of the Earth equal 40000 kilometres, or 21600 nautical miles.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] Those are the numbers of the corresponding angle units in one complete turn.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] Those definitions of the metre and the nautical mile have been superseded by more precise ones, but the original definitions are still accurate enough for conceptual purposes and some calculations.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] For example, they imply that one kilometre is exactly 0.54 nautical miles.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] Using official modern definitions, one nautical mile is exactly 1.852 kilometres, which implies that 1 kilometre is about 0.53995680 nautical miles.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] This modern ratio differs from the one calculated from the original definitions by less than one part in 10,000.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] For much of the history of mathematics, even the greatest thinkers considered it impossible to compute the length of an irregular arc.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] Although Archimedes had pioneered a way of finding the area beneath a curve with his "method of exhaustion", few believed it was even possible for curves to have definite lengths, as do straight lines.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] The first ground was broken in this field, as it often has been in calculus, by approximation.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] People began to inscribe polygons within the curves and compute the length of the sides for a somewhat accurate measurement of the length.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] By using more segments, and by decreasing the length of each segment, they were able to obtain a more and more accurate approximation.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] In particular, by inscribing a polygon of many sides in a circle, they were able to find approximate values of π.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] In 1659, Wallis credited William Neile's discovery of the first rectification of a nontrivial algebraic curve, the semicubical parabola.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] The accompanying figures appear on page 145.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] On page 91, William Neile is mentioned as *Gulielmus Nelius*.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] Before the full formal development of calculus, the basis for the modern integral form for arc length was independently discovered by Hendrik van Heuraet and Pierre de Fermat.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] In 1659 van Heuraet published a construction showing that the problem of determining arc length could be transformed into the problem of determining the area under a curve (i.e., an integral).
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] As an example of his method, he determined the arc length of a semicubical parabola, which required finding the area under a parabola.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] In 1660, Fermat published a more general theory containing the same result in his *De linearum curvarum cum lineis rectis comparatione dissertatio geometrica* (Geometric dissertation on curved lines in comparison with straight lines).
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] Next, he increased *a* by a small amount to *a* + *ε*, making segment *AC* a relatively good approximation for the length of the curve from *A* to *D*.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] In order to approximate the length, Fermat would sum up a sequence of short segments.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] As mentioned above, some curves are non-rectifiable.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] That is, there is no upper bound on the lengths of polygonal approximations; the length can be made arbitrarily large.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] Informally, such curves are said to have infinite length.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] There are continuous curves on which every arc (other than a single-point arc) has infinite length.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] An example of such a curve is the Koch curve.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] Another example of a curve with infinite length is the graph of the function defined by *f*(*x*) = *x* sin(1/*x*) for any open set with 0 as one of its delimiters and *f*(0) = 0.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] Sometimes the Hausdorff dimension and Hausdorff measure are used to quantify the size of such curves.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] is the tangent vector of $\gamma$ at $t.$ The sign in the square root is chosen once for a given curve, to ensure that the square root is a real number.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] The positive sign is chosen for spacelike curves; in a pseudo-Riemannian manifold, the negative sign may be chosen for timelike curves.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] Thus the length of a curve is a non-negative real number.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] Usually no curves are considered which are partly spacelike and partly timelike.
[src:continuation-methods/arc-length] In theory of relativity, arc length of timelike curves (world lines) is the proper time elapsed along the world line, and arc length of a spacelike curve the proper distance along the curve.
[src:continuation-methods/bifurcation-theory] The name "bifurcation" was first introduced by Henri Poincaré in 1885 in the first paper in mathematics showing such a behavior.
[src:continuation-methods/bifurcation-theory] A local bifurcation occurs when a parameter change causes the stability of an equilibrium (or fixed point) to change.
[src:continuation-methods/bifurcation-theory] In continuous systems, this corresponds to the real part of an eigenvalue of an equilibrium passing through zero.
[src:continuation-methods/bifurcation-theory] In discrete systems (described by maps), this corresponds to a fixed point having a Floquet multiplier with modulus equal to one.
[src:continuation-methods/bifurcation-theory] In both cases, the equilibrium is *non-hyperbolic* at the bifurcation point.
[src:continuation-methods/bifurcation-theory] The topological changes in the phase portrait of the system can be confined to arbitrarily small neighbourhoods of the bifurcating fixed points by moving the bifurcation parameter close to the bifurcation point (hence "local").
[src:continuation-methods/bifurcation-theory] If the eigenvalue is equal to zero, the bifurcation is a steady-state bifurcation, but if the eigenvalue is non-zero but purely imaginary, this is a Hopf bifurcation.
[src:continuation-methods/bifurcation-theory] For discrete dynamical systems, consider the system $x_{n+1}=f(x_{n},\lambda ).$ Then a local bifurcation occurs at $(x_{0},\lambda _{0})$ if the matrix ${\textrm {d}}f_{x_{0},\lambda _{0}}$ has an eigenvalue with modulus equal to one.
[src:continuation-methods/bifurcation-theory] If the eigenvalue is equal to one, the bifurcation is either a saddle-node (often called fold bifurcation in maps), transcritical or pitchfork bifurcation.
[src:continuation-methods/bifurcation-theory] If the eigenvalue is equal to −1, it is a period-doubling (or flip) bifurcation, and otherwise, it is a Hopf bifurcation.
[src:continuation-methods/bifurcation-theory] Global bifurcations occur when "larger" invariant sets, such as periodic orbits, collide with equilibria.
[src:continuation-methods/bifurcation-theory] This causes changes in the topology of the trajectories in the phase space which cannot be confined to a small neighbourhood, as is the case with local bifurcations.
[src:continuation-methods/bifurcation-theory] In fact, the changes in topology extend out to an arbitrarily large distance (hence "global").
[src:continuation-methods/bifurcation-theory] Global bifurcations can also involve more complicated sets such as chaotic attractors (e.g. crises).
[src:continuation-methods/bifurcation-theory] The codimension of a bifurcation is the number of parameters which must be varied for the bifurcation to occur.
[src:continuation-methods/bifurcation-theory] This corresponds to the codimension of the parameter set for which the bifurcation occurs within the full space of parameters.
[src:continuation-methods/bifurcation-theory] Saddle-node bifurcations and Hopf bifurcations are the only generic local bifurcations which are really codimension-one (the others all having higher codimension).
[src:continuation-methods/bifurcation-theory] However, transcritical and pitchfork bifurcations are also often thought of as codimension-one, because the normal forms can be written with only one parameter.
[src:continuation-methods/bifurcation-theory] An example of a well-studied codimension-two bifurcation is the Bogdanov–Takens bifurcation.
[src:continuation-methods/bifurcation-theory] Bifurcation theory has been applied to connect quantum systems to the dynamics of their classical analogues in atomic systems, molecular systems, and resonant tunneling diodes.
[src:continuation-methods/bifurcation-theory] Bifurcation theory has also been applied to the study of laser dynamics and a number of theoretical examples which are difficult to access experimentally such as the kicked top and coupled quantum wells.
[src:continuation-methods/bifurcation-theory] The dominant reason for the link between quantum systems and bifurcations in the classical equations of motion is that at bifurcations, the signature of classical orbits becomes large, as Martin Gutzwiller points out in his classic work on quantum chaos.
[src:continuation-methods/bifurcation-theory] Many kinds of bifurcations have been studied with regard to links between classical and quantum dynamics including saddle node bifurcations, Hopf bifurcations, umbilic bifurcations, period doubling bifurcations, reconnection bifurcations, tangent bifurcations, and cusp bifurcations.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] The **homotopy analysis method** (**HAM**) is a semi-analytical technique to solve nonlinear ordinary/partial differential equations.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] The homotopy analysis method employs the concept of the homotopy from topology to generate a convergent series solution for nonlinear systems.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] This is enabled by utilizing a homotopy-Maclaurin series to deal with the nonlinearities in the system.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] The HAM was first applied to calculate the ballistic transport of hot electrons in inhomogeneous sub-micron structures by solving a system of nonlinear differential equations in 1988 by Claus Hillebrand, RWTH Aachen.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] This was published in his thesis in 1989, see reference [4].
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] The convergence-control parameter is a non-physical variable that provides a simple way to verify and enforce convergence of a solution series.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] The capability of the HAM to naturally show convergence of the series solution is unusual in analytical and semi-analytic approaches to nonlinear partial differential equations.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] The HAM distinguishes itself from various other analytical methods in four important aspects.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] First, it is a series expansion method that is not directly dependent on small or large physical parameters.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] Thus, it is applicable for not only weakly but also strongly nonlinear problems, going beyond some of the inherent limitations of the standard perturbation methods.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] Second, the HAM is a unified method for the Lyapunov artificial small parameter method, the delta expansion method, the Adomian decomposition method, and the homotopy perturbation method.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] The greater generality of the method often allows for strong convergence of the solution over larger spatial and parameter domains.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] Third, the HAM gives excellent flexibility in the expression of the solution and how the solution is explicitly obtained.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] It provides great freedom to choose the basis functions of the desired solution and the corresponding auxiliary linear operator of the homotopy.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] Finally, unlike the other analytic approximation techniques, the HAM provides a simple way to ensure the convergence of the solution series.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] The homotopy analysis method is also able to combine with other techniques employed in nonlinear differential equations such as spectral methods and Padé approximants.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] It may further be combined with computational methods, such as the boundary element method to allow the linear method to solve nonlinear systems.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] Different from the numerical technique of homotopy continuation, the homotopy analysis method is an analytic approximation method as opposed to a discrete computational method.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] In the last twenty years, the HAM has been applied to solve a growing number of nonlinear ordinary/partial differential equations in science, finance, and engineering.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] For example, multiple steady-state resonant waves in deep and finite water depth were found with the wave resonance criterion of arbitrary number of traveling gravity waves; this agreed with Phillips' criterion for four waves with small amplitude.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] Further, a unified wave model applied with the HAM, admits not only the traditional smooth progressive periodic/solitary waves, but also the progressive solitary waves with peaked crest in finite water depth.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] This model shows peaked solitary waves are consistent solutions along with the known smooth ones.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] where ${\mathcal {N}}$ is a nonlinear operator.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] Let ${\mathcal {L}}$ denote an auxiliary linear operator, *u*0(*x*) an initial guess of *u*(*x*), and *c*0 a constant (called the convergence-control parameter), respectively.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] called the zeroth-order deformation equation, whose solution varies continuously with respect to the embedding parameter *q* ∈ [0,1].
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] with known initial guess *U*(*x*; 0) = *u*0(*x*) when *q* = 0, but is equivalent to the original nonlinear equation ${\mathcal {N}}[u(x)]=0$ , when *q* = 1, i.e.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] Therefore, as *q* increases from 0 to 1, the solution *U*(*x*; *q*) of the zeroth-order deformation equation varies (or deforms) from the chosen initial guess *u*0(*x*) to the solution *u*(*x*) of the considered nonlinear equation.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] called the *m*th-order deformation equation, where $\chi _{1}=0$ and $\chi _{k}=1$ for *k* > 1, and the right-hand side *R**m* is dependent only upon the known results *u*0, *u*1, ..., *u**m* − 1 and can be obtained easily using computer algebra software.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] In this way, the original nonlinear equation is transferred into an infinite number of linear ones, but without the assumption of any small/large physical parameters.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] Since the HAM is based on a homotopy, one has great freedom to choose the initial guess *u*0(*x*), the auxiliary linear operator ${\mathcal {L}}$ , and the convergence-control parameter *c*0 in the zeroth-order deformation equation.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] Thus, the HAM provides the mathematician freedom to choose the equation-type of the high-order deformation equation and the base functions of its solution.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] The optimal value of the convergence-control parameter *c*0 is determined by the minimum of the squared residual error of governing equations and/or boundary conditions after the general form has been solved for the chosen initial guess and linear operator.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] Thus, the convergence-control parameter *c*0 is a simple way to guarantee the convergence of the homotopy series solution and differentiates the HAM from other analytic approximation methods.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] The method overall gives a useful generalization of the concept of homotopy.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] Inspired by the recent successful applications of the HAM in different fields, a Mathematica package based on the HAM, called BVPh, has been made available online for solving nonlinear boundary-value problems [5].
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] BVPh is a solver package for highly nonlinear ODEs with singularities, multiple solutions, and multipoint boundary conditions in either a finite or an infinite interval, and includes support for certain types of nonlinear PDEs.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] Another HAM-based Mathematica code, APOh, has been produced to solve for an explicit analytic approximation of the optimal exercise boundary of American put option, which is also available online [6].
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] The HAM has recently been reported to be useful for obtaining analytical solutions for nonlinear frequency response equations.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] Such solutions are able to capture various nonlinear behaviors such as hardening-type, softening-type or mixed behaviors of the oscillator.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy-analysis-method] These analytical equations are also useful in prediction of chaos in nonlinear systems.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] A notable use of homotopy is the definition of homotopy groups and cohomotopy groups, important invariants in algebraic topology.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] In practice, there are technical difficulties in using homotopies with certain spaces.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] Algebraic topologists work with compactly generated spaces, CW complexes, or spectra.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] If we think of the second parameter of *H* as time, then *H* describes a *continuous deformation* of *f* into *g*: at time 0, we have the function *f*, and at time 1, we have the function *g*.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] We can also think of the second parameter as a "slider control" that allows us to smoothly transition from *f* to *g* as the slider moves from 0 to 1, and vice versa.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] An alternative notation is to say that a homotopy between two continuous functions $f,g:X\to Y$ is a family of continuous functions $h_{t}:X\to Y$ for $t\in [0,1]$ such that $h_{0}=f$ and $h_{1}=g$ , and the map $(x,t)\mapsto h_{t}(x)$ is continuous from $X\times [0,1]$ to Y .
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] The two versions coincide by setting $h_{t}(x)=H(x,t)$ .
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] It is not sufficient to require each map $h_{t}(x)$ to be continuous.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] The animation that is looped above right provides an example of a homotopy between two embeddings, *f* and *g*, of the torus into *R*3.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] *X* is the torus, *Y* is *R*3, *f* is some continuous function from the torus to *R*3 that takes the torus to the embedded surface-of-a-doughnut shape with which the animation starts; *g* is some continuous function that takes the torus to the embedded surface-of-a-coffee-mug shape.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] The animation shows the image of *h**t*(X) as a function of the parameter *t*, where *t* varies with time from 0 to 1 over each cycle of the animation loop.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] It pauses, then shows the image as *t* varies back from 1 to 0, pauses, and repeats this cycle.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] Continuous functions *f* and *g* are said to be homotopic if and only if there is a homotopy *H* taking *f* to *g* as described above.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] Being homotopic is an equivalence relation on the set of all continuous functions from *X* to *Y*.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] This homotopy relation is compatible with function composition in the following sense: if *f*1, *g*1 : *X* → *Y* are homotopic, and *f*2, *g*2 : *Y* → *Z* are homotopic, then their compositions *f*2 ∘ *f*1 and *g*2 ∘ *g*1 : *X* → *Z* are also homotopic.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] Given two topological spaces *X* and *Y*, a **homotopy equivalence** between *X* and *Y* is a pair of continuous maps *f* : *X* → *Y* and *g* : *Y* → *X*, such that *g* ∘ *f* is homotopic to the identity map id*X* and *f* ∘ *g* is homotopic to id*Y*.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] If such a pair exists, then *X* and *Y* are said to be **homotopy equivalent**, or of the same **homotopy type**.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] This relation of homotopy equivalence is often denoted $\simeq$ .
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] Intuitively, two spaces *X* and *Y* are homotopy equivalent if they can be transformed into one another by bending, shrinking and expanding operations.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] Spaces that are homotopy equivalent to a point are called contractible.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] A homeomorphism is a special case of a homotopy equivalence, in which *g* ∘ *f* is equal to the identity map id*X* (not only homotopic to it), and *f* ∘ *g* is equal to id*Y*.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] Therefore, if X and Y are homeomorphic, then they are homotopy equivalent, but the opposite is not true.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] A function f is said to be **null-homotopic** if it is homotopic to a constant function.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] (The homotopy from f to a constant function is then sometimes called a **null-homotopy**.) For example, a map f from the unit circle $S^{1}$ to any space X is null-homotopic precisely when it can be continuously extended to a map from the unit disk $D^{2}$ to X that agrees with f on the boundary.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] It follows from these definitions that a space X is contractible if and only if the identity map from X to itself—which is always a homotopy equivalence—is null-homotopic.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] Homotopy equivalence is important because in algebraic topology many concepts are **homotopy invariant**, that is, they respect the relation of homotopy equivalence.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] An example of an algebraic invariant of topological spaces which is not homotopy invariant is compactly supported homology (which is, roughly speaking, the homology of the compactification, and compactification is not homotopy invariant).
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] In order to define the fundamental group, one needs the notion of **homotopy relative to a subspace**.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] These are homotopies which keep the elements of the subspace fixed.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] Also, if *g* is a retraction from *X* to *K* and *f* is the identity map, this is known as a strong deformation retract of *X* to *K*.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] When *K* is a point, the term **pointed homotopy** is used.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] since one cannot be deformed into the other through a continuous path of homeomorphisms of the ambient space.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] When two given continuous functions *f* and *g* from the topological space *X* to the topological space *Y* are embeddings, one can ask whether they can be connected 'through embeddings'.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] This gives rise to the concept of **isotopy**, which is a homotopy, *H*, in the notation used before, such that for each fixed *t*, *H*(*x*, *t*) gives an embedding.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] A related, but separate, concept is that of ambient isotopy.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] Requiring that two embeddings be isotopic is a stronger requirement than that they be homotopic.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] For example, the map from the interval [−1, 1] into the real numbers defined by *f*(*x*) = −*x* is *not* isotopic to the identity *g*(*x*) = *x*.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] Any homotopy from *f* to the identity would have to exchange the endpoints, which would mean that they would have to 'pass through' each other.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] Moreover, *f* has changed the orientation of the interval and *g* has not, which is impossible under an isotopy.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] Two homeomorphisms (which are special cases of embeddings) of the unit ball which agree on the boundary can be shown to be isotopic using Alexander's trick.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] For this reason, the map of the unit disc in $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ defined by *f*(*x*, *y*) = (−*x*, −*y*) is isotopic to a 180-degree rotation around the origin, and so the identity map and *f* are isotopic because they can be connected by rotations.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] In geometric topology—for example, in knot theory—the idea of isotopy is used to construct equivalence relations.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] For example, when should two knots be considered the same?
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] We take two knots, *K*1 and *K*2, in three-dimensional space.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] A knot is an embedding of a one-dimensional space, the "loop of string" (or the circle), into this space, and this embedding gives a homeomorphism between the circle and its image in the embedding space.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] One may try to define knot equivalence based on isotopy instead of the more restricted property of ambient isotopy.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] That is, two knots are isotopic when there exists a continuous function starting at *t* = 0 giving the *K*1 embedding, ending at *t* = 1 giving the *K*2 embedding, with all intermediate values corresponding to embeddings.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] However, this definition would make every knot equivalent to the unknot, as the knotted portions can be "contracted" down to a straight line.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] The problem is that, while continuous, this is not an injective function of the Euclidean space that the knot is embedded in.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] An ambient isotopy, studied in this context, is an isotopy of the larger space, considered in light of its action on the embedded submanifold.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] Knots *K*1 and *K*2 are considered equivalent when there is a continuous [0, 1]-indexed family of maps which moves *K*1 to *K*2 via homeomorphisms of the Euclidean space.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] Similar language is used for the equivalent concept in contexts where one has a stronger notion of equivalence.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] For example, a path between two smooth embeddings is a **smooth isotopy**.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] On a Lorentzian manifold, certain curves are distinguished as timelike (representing something that only goes forwards, not backwards, in time, in every local frame).
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] A timelike homotopy between two timelike curves is a homotopy such that the curve remains timelike during the continuous transformation from one curve to another.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] No closed timelike curve (CTC) on a Lorentzian manifold is timelike homotopic to a point (that is, null timelike homotopic); such a manifold is therefore said to be multiply connected by timelike curves.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] A manifold such as the 3-sphere can be simply connected (by any type of curve), and yet be timelike multiply connected.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] The homotopy lifting property is used to characterize fibrations.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] Another useful property involving homotopy is the homotopy extension property, which characterizes the extension of a homotopy between two functions from a subset of some set to the set itself.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] It is useful when dealing with cofibrations.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] Since the relation of two functions $f,g\colon X\to Y$ being homotopic relative to a subspace is an equivalence relation, we can look at the equivalence classes of maps between a fixed *X* and *Y*.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] If we fix $X=[0,1]^{n}$ , the unit interval [0, 1] crossed with itself *n* times, and we take its boundary $\partial ([0,1]^{n})$ as a subspace, then the equivalence classes form a group, denoted $\pi _{n}(Y,y_{0})$ , where $y_{0}$ is in the image of the subspace $\partial ([0,1]^{n})$ .
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] We can define the action of one equivalence class on another, and so we get a group.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] These groups are called the homotopy groups.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] In the case $n=1$ , it is also called the fundamental group.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] The idea of homotopy can be turned into a formal category of category theory.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] The **homotopy category** is the category whose objects are topological spaces, and whose morphisms are homotopy equivalence classes of continuous maps.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] Two topological spaces *X* and *Y* are isomorphic in this category if and only if they are homotopy equivalent.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] Then a functor on the category of topological spaces is homotopy invariant if it can be expressed as a functor on the homotopy category.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] For example, homology groups are a *functorial* homotopy invariant: this means that if *f* and *g* from *X* to *Y* are homotopic, then the group homomorphisms induced by *f* and *g* on the level of homology groups are the same: H*n*(*f*) = H*n*(*g*) : H*n*(*X*) → H*n*(*Y*) for all *n*.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] Likewise, if *X* and *Y* are in addition path-connected, and the homotopy between *f* and *g* is pointed, then the group homomorphisms induced by *f* and *g* on the level of homotopy groups are also the same: π*n*(*f*) = π*n*(*g*) : π*n*(*X*) → π*n*(*Y*).
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] Based on the concept of the homotopy, computation methods for algebraic and differential equations have been developed.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] The methods for algebraic equations include the homotopy continuation method and the continuation method (see numerical continuation).
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] The methods for differential equations include the homotopy analysis method.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] Homotopy theory can be used as a foundation for homology theory: one can represent a cohomology functor on a space *X* by mappings of *X* into an appropriate fixed space, up to homotopy equivalence.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] For example, for any abelian group *G*, and any based CW-complex *X*, the set $[X,K(G,n)]$ of based homotopy classes of based maps from *X* to the Eilenberg–MacLane space $K(G,n)$ is in natural bijection with the *n*-th singular cohomology group $H^{n}(X,G)$ of the space *X*.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] One says that the omega-spectrum of Eilenberg-MacLane spaces are representing spaces for singular cohomology with coefficients in *G*.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] Using this fact, homotopy classes between a CW complex and a multiply connected space can be calculated using cohomology as described by the Hopf–Whitney theorem.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] Recently, homotopy theory is used to develop deep learning-based generative models like diffusion models and flow-based generative models.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] Perturbing the complex non-Gaussian states is a tough task.
[src:continuation-methods/homotopy] Using deep learning and homotopy, such complex states can be transformed to Gaussian state and mildly perturbed to get transformed back to perturbed complex states.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] The parameter $\lambda$ is usually a real scalar and the *solution* $\mathbf {u}$ is an *n*-vector.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] For a fixed parameter value $\lambda$ , ${\textstyle F(\cdot ,\lambda )}$ maps Euclidean n-space into itself.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] Often the original mapping F is from a Banach space into itself, and the Euclidean n-space is a finite-dimensional Banach space.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] A steady state, or fixed point, of a parameterized family of flows or maps are of this form, and by discretizing trajectories of a flow or iterating a map, periodic orbits and heteroclinic orbits can also be posed as a solution of $F=0$ .
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] In some nonlinear systems, parameters are explicit.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] where $\mathbf {u}$ is an *n*-vector, and its image $F(\mathbf {u} )$ is an *n*−1 vector.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] However, in an algebraic system there is no distinction between unknowns $\mathbf {u}$ and the parameters.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] A periodic motion is a closed curve in phase space.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] The textbook example of a periodic motion is the undamped pendulum.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] The second step is to add an additional equation, a *phase constraint*, that can be thought of as determining the period.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] This is necessary because any solution of the above boundary value problem can be shifted in time by an arbitrary amount (time does not appear in the defining equations—the dynamical system is called autonomous).
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] There are several choices for the phase constraint.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] which states that $\mathbf {u}$ lies in a plane which is orthogonal to the tangent vector of the closed curve.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] This plane is called a *Poincaré section*.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] A regular point of F is a point $(\mathbf {u} ,\lambda )$ at which the Jacobian of F is full rank $(n)$ .
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] Near a regular point the solution component is an isolated curve passing through the regular point (the implicit function theorem).
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] In the figure above the point $(\mathbf {u} _{0},\lambda _{0})$ is a regular point.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] A singular point of F is a point $(\mathbf {u} ,\lambda )$ at which the Jacobian of F is not full rank.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] Near a singular point the solution component may not be an isolated curve passing through the regular point.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] The local structure is determined by higher derivatives of F .
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] In the figure above the point where the two blue curves cross is a singular point.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] In general solution components $\Gamma$ are branched curves.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] Finding the solution curves leaving a singular point is called branch switching, and uses techniques from bifurcation theory (singularity theory, catastrophe theory).
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] For finite-dimensional systems (as defined above) the Lyapunov-Schmidt decomposition may be used to produce two systems to which the Implicit Function Theorem applies.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] The Lyapunov-Schmidt decomposition uses the restriction of the system to the complement of the null space of the Jacobian and the range of the Jacobian.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] where $\eta$ is in the complement of the null space of J $(\Phi ^{T}\,\eta =0)$ .
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] In the first equation, which is parametrized by the null space of the Jacobian ( $\xi$ ), the Jacobian with respect to $\eta$ is non-singular.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] So the implicit function theorem states that there is a mapping $\eta (\xi )$ such that $\eta (0)=0$ and $(I-\Psi \Psi ^{T})F(x+\Phi \xi +\eta (\xi ))=0)$ .
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] The second equation (with $\eta (\xi )$ substituted) is called the bifurcation equation (though it may be a system of equations).
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] The bifurcation equation has a Taylor expansion which lacks the constant and linear terms.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] By scaling the equations and the null space of the Jacobian of the original system a system can be found with non-singular Jacobian.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] Another type of singular point is a turning point bifurcation, or saddle-node bifurcation, where the direction of the parameter $\lambda$ reverses as the curve is followed.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] The red curve in the figure above illustrates a turning point.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] Most methods of solution of nonlinear systems of equations are iterative methods.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] For a particular parameter value $\lambda _{0}$ a mapping is repeatedly applied to an initial guess $\mathbf {u} _{0}$ .
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] If the method converges, and is consistent, then in the limit the iteration approaches a solution of $F(\mathbf {u} ,\lambda _{0})=0$ .
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] One advantage of natural parameter continuation is that it uses the solution method for the problem as a black box.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] All that is required is that an initial solution be given (some solvers used to always start at a fixed initial guess).
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] There has been a lot of work in the area of large scale continuation on applying more sophisticated algorithms to black box solvers (see e.g.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] However, natural parameter continuation fails at turning points, where the branch of solutions turns round.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] So for problems with turning points, a more sophisticated method such as pseudo-arclength continuation must be used (see below).
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] Simplicial Continuation, or Piecewise Linear Continuation (Allgower and Georg) is based on three basic results.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] Please see the article on piecewise linear continuation for details.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] With these two operations this continuation algorithm is easy to state (although of course an efficient implementation requires a more sophisticated approach.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] An initial simplex is assumed to be given, from a reference simplicial decomposition of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] The initial simplex must have at least one face which contains a zero of the unique linear interpolant on that face.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] The other faces of the simplex are then tested, and typically there will be one additional face with an interior zero.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] The initial simplex is then replaced by the simplex which lies across either face containing zero, and the process is repeated.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] References: Allgower and Georg [B1] provides a crisp, clear description of the algotihm.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] This method is based on the observation that the "ideal" parameterization of a curve is arclength.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] Pseudo-arclength is an approximation of the arclength in the tangent space of the curve.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] The resulting modified natural continuation method makes a step in pseudo-arclength (rather than $\lambda$ ).
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] The iterative solver is required to find a point at the given pseudo-arclength, which requires appending an additional constraint (the pseudo-arclength constraint) to the n by $n+1$ Jacobian.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] It produces a square Jacobian, and if the stepsize is sufficiently small the modified Jacobian is full rank.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] Pseudo-arclength continuation was independently developed by Edward Riks and Gerald Wempner for finite element applications in the late 1960s, and published in journals in the early 1970s by H.B.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] A detailed account of these early developments is provided in the textbook by M.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] Crisfield: Nonlinear Finite Element Analysis of Solids and Structures, Vol 1: Basic Concepts, Wiley, 1991.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] Crisfield was one of the most active developers of this class of methods, which are by now standard procedures of commercial nonlinear finite element programs.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] The algorithm is a predictor-corrector method.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] The prediction is corrected by searching in the direction transverse to the tangent vector.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] At regular points, where the unmodified Jacobian is full rank, the tangent vector spans the null space of the top row of this new Jacobian.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] Appending the tangent vector as the last row can be seen as determining the coefficient of the null vector in the general solution of the Newton system (particular solution plus an arbitrary multiple of the null vector).
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] This method is a variant of pseudo-arclength continuation.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] Instead of using the tangent at the initial point in the arclength constraint, the tangent at the current solution is used.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] The parameter $\lambda$ in the algorithms described above is a real scalar.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] Most physical and design problems generally have many more than one parameter.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] Higher-dimensional continuation refers to the case when $\lambda$ is a k-vector.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] A **regular solution** is a solution at which the Jacobian is full rank $(n)$ .
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] A singular solution is a solution at which the Jacobian is less than full rank.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] A regular solution lies on a k-dimensional surface, which can be parameterized by a point in the tangent space (the null space of the Jacobian).
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] This is again a straightforward application of the Implicit Function Theorem.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] Numerical continuation techniques have found a great degree of acceptance in the study of chaotic dynamical systems and various other systems which belong to the realm of catastrophe theory.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] The reason for such usage stems from the fact that various non-linear dynamical systems behave in a deterministic and predictable manner within a range of parameters which are included in the equations of the system.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] However, for a certain parameter value the system starts behaving chaotically and hence it became necessary to follow the parameter in order to be able to decipher the occurrences of when the system starts being non-predictable, and what exactly (theoretically) makes the system become unstable.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] Analysis of parameter continuation can lead to more insights about stable/critical point bifurcations.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] Study of saddle-node, transcritical, pitch-fork, period doubling, Hopf, secondary Hopf (Neimark) bifurcations of stable solutions allows for a theoretical discussion of the circumstances and occurrences which arise at the critical points.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] Parameter continuation also gives a more dependable system to analyze a dynamical system as it is more stable than more interactive, time-stepped numerical solutions.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] Especially in cases where the dynamical system is prone to blow-up at certain parameter values (or combination of values for multiple parameters).
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] The study of turbulence is another field where the Numerical Continuation techniques have been used to study the advent of turbulence in a system starting at low Reynolds numbers.
[src:continuation-methods/numerical-continuation] This problem, of finding the points which *F* maps into the origin appears in computer graphics as the problems of drawing contour maps (n=2), or isosurface (n=3).
[src:continuation-methods/predictor-corrector-method] In numerical analysis, **predictor–corrector methods** belong to a class of algorithms designed to integrate ordinary differential equations – to find an unknown function that satisfies a given differential equation.
[src:continuation-methods/predictor-corrector-method] The next, "corrector" step refines the initial approximation by using the *predicted* value of the function and *another method* to interpolate that unknown function's value at the **same** subsequent point.
[src:continuation-methods/predictor-corrector-method] When considering the numerical solution of ordinary differential equations (ODEs), a predictor–corrector method typically uses an explicit method for the predictor step and an implicit method for the corrector step.
[src:continuation-methods/predictor-corrector-method] A simple predictor–corrector method (known as Heun's method) can be constructed from the Euler method (an explicit method) and the trapezoidal rule (an implicit method).
[src:continuation-methods/predictor-corrector-method] There are different variants of a predictor–corrector method, depending on how often the corrector method is applied.
[src:continuation-methods/predictor-corrector-method] Additionally, the corrector step can be repeated in the hope that this achieves an even better approximation to the true solution.
[src:continuation-methods/predictor-corrector-method] The PECEC mode has one fewer function evaluation than PECECE mode.
[src:continuation-methods/predictor-corrector-method] More generally, if the corrector is run *k* times, the method is in P(EC)*k* or P(EC)*k*E mode.
[src:continuation-methods/predictor-corrector-method] If the corrector method is iterated until it converges, this could be called PE(CE)∞.
[src:continuation-methods/saddle-node-bifurcation] In the mathematical area of bifurcation theory a **saddle-node bifurcation**, **tangential bifurcation** or **fold bifurcation** is a local bifurcation in which two fixed points (or equilibria) of a dynamical system collide and annihilate each other.
[src:continuation-methods/saddle-node-bifurcation] The term 'saddle-node bifurcation' is most often used in reference to continuous dynamical systems.
[src:continuation-methods/saddle-node-bifurcation] In discrete dynamical systems, the same bifurcation is often instead called a **fold bifurcation**.
[src:continuation-methods/saddle-node-bifurcation] Another name is **blue sky bifurcation** in reference to the sudden creation of two fixed points.
[src:continuation-methods/saddle-node-bifurcation] If the phase space is one-dimensional, one of the equilibrium points is unstable (the saddle), while the other is stable (the node).
[src:continuation-methods/saddle-node-bifurcation] Saddle-node bifurcations may be associated with hysteresis loops and catastrophes.
[src:continuation-methods/saddle-node-bifurcation] Here x is the state variable and r is the bifurcation parameter.
[src:continuation-methods/saddle-node-bifurcation] In fact, this is a normal form of a saddle-node bifurcation.
[src:continuation-methods/saddle-node-bifurcation] The first condition is the nondegeneracy condition and the second condition is the transversality condition.
[src:continuation-methods/saddle-node-bifurcation] Other examples are in modelling biological switches.
[src:continuation-methods/saddle-node-bifurcation] Recently, it was shown that under certain conditions, the Einstein field equations of General Relativity have the same form as a fold bifurcation.
[src:continuation-methods/saddle-node-bifurcation] A non-autonomous version of the saddle-node bifurcation (i.e. the parameter is time-dependent) has also been studied.
